1
00:00:03,003 --> 00:00:05,130
ROSE: Peter Alan Tyler, my dad.

2
00:00:05,797 --> 00:00:08,008
The most wonderful man in the world.

3
00:00:08,091 --> 00:00:11,303
Born 15th September, 1954.

4
00:00:13,847 --> 00:00:16,058
Come here, Rose. Come here.

5
00:00:23,273 --> 00:00:26,193
Who's that? It's your daddy.

6
00:00:27,236 --> 00:00:30,072
You weren't old enough
to remember when he died.

7
00:00:30,864 --> 00:00:34,910
1987, 7th November.

8
00:00:34,993 --> 00:00:37,037
Do you remember
what I told you?

9
00:00:37,120 --> 00:00:40,666
The day that Stuart Hoskins
and Sarah Clark got married.

10
00:00:42,125 --> 00:00:44,253
He was always
having adventures.

11
00:00:45,087 --> 00:00:47,589
He would have loved
to have seen you now.

12
00:00:50,592 --> 00:00:52,803
That's what Mum always says.

13
00:00:52,886 --> 00:00:54,680
So I was thinking,

14
00:00:54,763 --> 00:00:58,642
could we go and see my dad
when he was still alive?

15
00:00:58,725 --> 00:01:00,686
Where's this come
from all of a sudden?

16
00:01:00,769 --> 00:01:04,064
All right, if we can't, if it goes
against the laws of time or something,

17
00:01:04,147 --> 00:01:05,566
then never mind,
just leave it.

18
00:01:05,649 --> 00:01:08,902
No, I can do anything.
I'm just more worried about you.

19
00:01:08,986 --> 00:01:10,153
I want to see him.

20
00:01:10,237 --> 00:01:13,657
Your wish is my command.
But be careful what you wish for.

21
00:01:21,123 --> 00:01:23,166
(DOCTOR WHO THEME MUSIC)

22
00:01:57,576 --> 00:01:59,828
I, Peter Alan Tyler,

23
00:01:59,911 --> 00:02:03,290
take you,
Jacqueline Andrea Suzette Prentice.

24
00:02:03,790 --> 00:02:06,126
I, Peter Alan Tyler,

25
00:02:06,251 --> 00:02:08,837
take you, Jacqueline...

26
00:02:08,962 --> 00:02:10,714
Susanne, Suzette...

27
00:02:11,965 --> 00:02:13,133
Anita?

28
00:02:17,638 --> 00:02:20,515
Just carry on.
It's good enough for Lady Di.

29
00:02:22,100 --> 00:02:23,644
I thought he'd be taller.

30
00:02:23,727 --> 00:02:28,774
To be my lawful wedded wife.
To love and behold till death us do part.

31
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:32,027
MUM: He died so close to home.

32
00:02:32,819 --> 00:02:35,614
I wasn't there. Nobody was.

33
00:02:36,490 --> 00:02:38,408
It was a hit-and-run driver.

34
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:40,952
Never found out who.

35
00:02:42,120 --> 00:02:44,581
He was dead
when the ambulance got there.

36
00:02:45,582 --> 00:02:48,502
I only wish there'd been
someone there for him.

37
00:02:53,548 --> 00:02:56,927
ROSE: I want to be that someone.
So he doesn't die alone.

38
00:02:57,386 --> 00:02:59,930
-November 7th?
-1987.

39
00:03:03,225 --> 00:03:05,394
(WHOOSHING)

40
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:27,999
It's so weird.

41
00:03:28,083 --> 00:03:29,793
The day my father died.

42
00:03:31,211 --> 00:03:35,090
I thought it'd be all sort of grim and stormy.
It's just an ordinary day.

43
00:03:35,173 --> 00:03:37,843
The past is another country.

44
00:03:37,926 --> 00:03:40,178
1987 is just the Isle of Wight.

45
00:03:42,139 --> 00:03:44,099
-You sure about this?
-Yeah.

46
00:03:57,279 --> 00:03:59,156
This is it. Jordan Road.

47
00:04:00,699 --> 00:04:02,617
He was late.

48
00:04:02,784 --> 00:04:05,787
He'd been to get a wedding present,
a vase.

49
00:04:06,705 --> 00:04:08,999
Mum always said,
"That stupid vase."

50
00:04:13,462 --> 00:04:15,756
He got out of his car...

51
00:04:16,882 --> 00:04:18,717
and crossed the road.

52
00:04:19,968 --> 00:04:22,012
Oh, God, this is it.

53
00:04:43,158 --> 00:04:45,160
Go to him. Quick.

54
00:04:55,003 --> 00:04:56,463
It's too late now.

55
00:04:58,256 --> 00:05:01,176
By the time the ambulance got there,
he was dead.

56
00:05:06,556 --> 00:05:08,308
He can't die on his own.

57
00:05:09,976 --> 00:05:11,353
Can I try again?

58
00:05:23,698 --> 00:05:26,076
Right, that's the first you and me.

59
00:05:26,201 --> 00:05:29,287
It's a very bad idea, two sets of us
being here at the same time.

60
00:05:29,371 --> 00:05:31,581
Just be careful
they don't see us.

61
00:05:31,665 --> 00:05:35,001
Wait till she runs off and he follows
then go to your dad.

62
00:05:45,303 --> 00:05:47,264
Oh, God, this is it.

63
00:05:54,145 --> 00:05:55,355
I can't do this.

64
00:05:55,438 --> 00:05:57,524
You don't have to do anything
you don't want to.

65
00:05:57,607 --> 00:06:00,193
But this is the last
time we can be here.

66
00:06:03,154 --> 00:06:04,447
Rose, no!

67
00:06:18,712 --> 00:06:21,339
I did it. I saved your life.

68
00:06:21,423 --> 00:06:24,217
Blimey, did you see the speed of it?
Did you get his number?

69
00:06:24,301 --> 00:06:28,054
I really did it.
Oh, my God, look at you, you're alive.

70
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:29,639
That car was gonna kill you.

71
00:06:29,723 --> 00:06:33,518
Give me some credit, I did see it coming.
I wasn't gonna walk under it, was I?

72
00:06:33,602 --> 00:06:35,395
I'm Rose.

73
00:06:38,356 --> 00:06:40,525
That's a coincidence.
That's my daughter's name.

74
00:06:41,484 --> 00:06:44,654
That's a great name.
Good choice. Well done.

75
00:06:49,492 --> 00:06:51,912
Right. I better shift.
I've got a wedding to go to.

76
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:54,623
-Is that Sarah Clark's wedding?
-Yeah. Are you going?

77
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:55,749
Yeah.

78
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:58,293
Do you and your
boyfriend need a lift?

79
00:07:05,258 --> 00:07:07,135
(SCREECHING)

80
00:07:09,804 --> 00:07:11,973
Right, there we go,
sorry about the mess.

81
00:07:12,057 --> 00:07:15,602
If you want a cup of tea,
kitchen's down there, milk's in the fridge.

82
00:07:15,685 --> 00:07:18,897
It would be, wouldn't it?
Where else would you put the milk?

83
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:21,483
Mind you, there's always
the windowsill outside.

84
00:07:21,566 --> 00:07:25,236
I always thought if someone invented
a windowsill with special compartments,

85
00:07:25,320 --> 00:07:27,197
one for milk, one for yoghurt,

86
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:30,992
make a lot of money out of that.
Sell it to students and things.

87
00:07:32,744 --> 00:07:34,079
I should write that down.

88
00:07:34,162 --> 00:07:37,207
Anyway, never mind that.
Excuse me, I got to go and change.

89
00:07:40,293 --> 00:07:42,963
All the stuff Mum kept.
His stuff.

90
00:07:43,838 --> 00:07:46,299
She kept it all packed away
in boxes in the cupboard.

91
00:07:46,383 --> 00:07:49,344
She used to show me
when she'd had a bit to drink.

92
00:07:49,678 --> 00:07:52,514
Here it is, on display.

93
00:07:53,682 --> 00:07:55,767
Where it should be.

94
00:07:59,437 --> 00:08:03,233
Third prize at the bowling.
First two got to go to Didcot.

95
00:08:05,860 --> 00:08:07,153
Health drinks.

96
00:08:07,237 --> 00:08:09,614
Tonics Mum used to call them.

97
00:08:09,698 --> 00:08:11,825
He made his money
selling this Vitex stuff.

98
00:08:11,908 --> 00:08:13,994
He had all sorts of jobs,
he was so clever.

99
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:20,583
Solar power.
Mum said he was going to do this.

100
00:08:20,667 --> 00:08:22,002
Now he can.

101
00:08:25,505 --> 00:08:28,091
Okay, I'll tell him
you're not my boyfriend.

102
00:08:28,174 --> 00:08:30,343
When we met I said,
"Travel with me in space.”

103
00:08:30,427 --> 00:08:31,553
You said, "No."

104
00:08:31,636 --> 00:08:33,346
Then I said, "Time machine."

105
00:08:33,430 --> 00:08:34,889
It wasn't some big plan.

106
00:08:34,973 --> 00:08:39,436
I just saw it happening,
and I thought, "I can stop it."

107
00:08:41,479 --> 00:08:43,815
I did it again.
I picked another stupid ape.

108
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:47,402
I should have known. It's not about
showing you the universe. It never is.

109
00:08:47,485 --> 00:08:49,779
It's about the universe
doing something for you.

110
00:08:49,863 --> 00:08:53,158
So it's okay when you go to other times
and you save people's lives

111
00:08:53,241 --> 00:08:54,909
but not when it's
me saving my dad?

112
00:08:54,993 --> 00:08:56,619
I know what I'm doing,
you don't.

113
00:08:56,703 --> 00:08:59,330
Two sets of us being there
made that a vulnerable point.

114
00:08:59,414 --> 00:09:00,582
But he's alive.

115
00:09:00,665 --> 00:09:02,834
My entire planet died,
my whole family.

116
00:09:02,917 --> 00:09:05,670
Do you think it never occurred to me
to go back and save them?

117
00:09:05,754 --> 00:09:07,964
But it's not like
I've changed history.

118
00:09:08,048 --> 00:09:09,340
Not much. I mean,

119
00:09:09,424 --> 00:09:13,470
he's never gonna be a world leader,
he's not gonna start World War III.

120
00:09:13,553 --> 00:09:16,806
Rose, there's a man alive in the world
who wasn't alive before.

121
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:20,018
An ordinary man.
That's the most important thing in creation.

122
00:09:20,101 --> 00:09:22,395
The whole world's different
because he's alive.

123
00:09:22,479 --> 00:09:24,856
-Would you rather him dead?
-I'm not saying that...

124
00:09:24,939 --> 00:09:28,193
No, I get it. For once, you're not
the most important man in my life.

125
00:09:28,276 --> 00:09:31,154
Let's see how you get on without me.
Give me the key.

126
00:09:31,237 --> 00:09:33,990
The Tardis key.
If I'm so insignificant, give it me back.

127
00:09:34,074 --> 00:09:35,700
All right then, I will.

128
00:09:35,784 --> 00:09:38,745
You've got what you wanted
so that's goodbye, then.

129
00:09:40,038 --> 00:09:42,499
You don't scare me.

130
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:45,543
I know how sad you are.
You'll be back in a minute.

131
00:09:45,668 --> 00:09:48,922
Or you'll hang around
outside the Tardis waiting for me.

132
00:09:49,255 --> 00:09:51,591
And I'll make you
wait a long time.

133
00:09:58,389 --> 00:09:59,849
Boyfriend trouble?

134
00:10:13,154 --> 00:10:14,906
(SCREECHING)

135
00:10:33,508 --> 00:10:34,801
(MAN SCREAMS)

136
00:10:37,512 --> 00:10:38,972
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

137
00:10:47,814 --> 00:10:50,275
Excuse me, do you mind?
What are you tidying up for?

138
00:10:50,358 --> 00:10:52,485
Sorry, force of habit.

139
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:55,530
Don't worry about him.
Couples have rows all the time.

140
00:10:55,613 --> 00:10:59,033
We're not a couple.
Why does everyone think we're a couple?

141
00:11:01,202 --> 00:11:04,080
-I think he left me.
-What? A pretty girl like you?

142
00:11:04,164 --> 00:11:06,541
-If I was going out with you...
-Stop right there.

143
00:11:06,624 --> 00:11:07,667
I'm just saying...

144
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:10,170
I know what you're saying
and we're not going there.

145
00:11:10,253 --> 00:11:13,631
At no point are we going
anywhere near there.

146
00:11:13,715 --> 00:11:16,926
You aren't even aware
that there exists...

147
00:11:17,010 --> 00:11:19,971
I don't want to think about there and,
believe me, neither do you.

148
00:11:20,054 --> 00:11:23,766
There, for you, is like...

149
00:11:23,850 --> 00:11:25,685
like the Bermuda Triangle.

150
00:11:26,227 --> 00:11:29,647
-Blimey, you know how to flatter a bloke.
-Right. Are we off?

151
00:11:29,731 --> 00:11:33,234
-That wouldn't be a mixed signal at all?
-Absolutely not.

152
00:11:34,027 --> 00:11:36,905
I'll take you back to the loony bin
where you belong.

153
00:11:36,988 --> 00:11:39,741
Except I'm sure
I've met you somewhere before.

154
00:11:41,409 --> 00:11:43,244
(CHURCH ORGAN MUSIC)

155
00:11:47,874 --> 00:11:49,709
-It's weird.
-What?

156
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:51,294
There's so many people missing.

157
00:11:51,377 --> 00:11:54,005
Uncle Steven, Auntie Lynn,
all the Baxters.

158
00:11:54,214 --> 00:11:56,132
Where are they?

159
00:11:56,216 --> 00:11:57,967
You don't think
something's gone wrong?

160
00:11:58,051 --> 00:12:01,179
Maybe it's a godsend,
gives you time to think.

161
00:12:01,346 --> 00:12:04,057
You don't have to go through with it,
not these days.

162
00:12:04,140 --> 00:12:06,100
-Live in sin for a bit.
-Dad.

163
00:12:06,184 --> 00:12:10,855
In 10 years' time, you'll turn round and say,
"If only I could turn the clock back."

164
00:12:16,110 --> 00:12:18,321
Is it me or did it just get cold?

165
00:12:20,531 --> 00:12:22,158
(BIRD CAWING)

166
00:12:57,735 --> 00:12:58,861
Rose.

167
00:13:02,073 --> 00:13:05,410
I met this bloke at the horses
and he's cutting me in on copyright.

168
00:13:05,493 --> 00:13:07,704
But I thought you were
a proper businessman.

169
00:13:07,787 --> 00:13:10,915
I wish. I do a bit of this, bit of that.
I scrape by.

170
00:13:11,457 --> 00:13:14,335
Right. I must've heard wrong.

171
00:13:14,419 --> 00:13:17,505
So, really,
you're a bit of a Del Boy.

172
00:13:17,588 --> 00:13:19,132
Shoot me down in flames.

173
00:13:19,215 --> 00:13:22,343
You're not related to my wife
by any chance, are you?

174
00:13:23,177 --> 00:13:25,388
Oh, my God.
She's gonna be at the wedding.

175
00:13:25,471 --> 00:13:27,598
Jackie? Do you know her?

176
00:13:29,559 --> 00:13:30,727
Sort of.

177
00:13:31,227 --> 00:13:33,021
What's she told you about me, then?

178
00:13:33,104 --> 00:13:36,482
She said she'd picked
the most fantastic man in the world.

179
00:13:37,692 --> 00:13:40,903
Must be a different Jackie, then.
She'd never say that.

180
00:13:41,946 --> 00:13:43,614
(RAP MUSIC)

181
00:13:43,698 --> 00:13:45,908
This stuff goes
right over my head.

182
00:13:46,701 --> 00:13:49,162
-That's not out yet.
-Good job and all.

183
00:13:49,245 --> 00:13:53,333
-I'm just gonna check my messages.
-How do you mean? Messages?

184
00:13:55,001 --> 00:13:56,961
-Is that a phone?
-Yeah.

185
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:02,300
MAN: Watson, come here.
I need you.

186
00:14:03,176 --> 00:14:05,595
Watson, come here. I need you.

187
00:14:06,763 --> 00:14:09,307
Watson, come here. I need you.

188
00:14:23,696 --> 00:14:25,948
Half the guests haven't turned up.

189
00:14:26,032 --> 00:14:29,702
You're better off not being here,
it's a disaster in the making.

190
00:14:30,620 --> 00:14:34,540
No, in this case,
"knocked her up” is a phrase I'd use.

191
00:14:34,624 --> 00:14:36,834
Watson, come here. I need you.

192
00:14:36,918 --> 00:14:38,628
Hello? Who's this?

193
00:14:38,711 --> 00:14:40,546
Watson, come here. I...

194
00:14:42,632 --> 00:14:45,760
Dad, get inside.
We can't see the bride before the wedding.

195
00:14:45,843 --> 00:14:47,929
-That's bad luck.
-Bad luck when you met her.

196
00:14:48,012 --> 00:14:50,181
I tell you, this day is cursed.

197
00:15:01,776 --> 00:15:04,070
Now that's what I call a meringue.

198
00:15:04,153 --> 00:15:07,532
Stuart's dad said go round the block
"cause there's people missing.

199
00:15:07,615 --> 00:15:08,783
How do you mean, missing?

200
00:15:08,866 --> 00:15:11,494
There's no Dave, no Sunita, no Bee...

201
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:13,329
There's no one from The Lamb and Flag.

202
00:15:13,413 --> 00:15:16,707
My train's detached again.
I knew I should have used Velcro.

203
00:15:16,791 --> 00:15:18,626
I'm here, stop your bellyaching.

204
00:15:18,709 --> 00:15:20,294
Take Rose a sec, will you?

205
00:15:20,378 --> 00:15:21,504
Ain't she pretty?

206
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:23,506
She's a little madam,
that's what she is.

207
00:15:23,589 --> 00:15:24,882
I need more hands.

208
00:15:24,966 --> 00:15:27,927
Where's her useless article
of a dad got to?

209
00:15:36,686 --> 00:15:37,770
Dad!

210
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:43,151
It's that car.
Same one as before.

211
00:15:46,737 --> 00:15:49,449
It was right in front of us,
where's he gone?

212
00:15:51,993 --> 00:15:54,162
You called me "Dad"?
What did you say that for?

213
00:15:54,245 --> 00:15:58,082
Oh, wonderful! Here he is,
the accident waiting to happen.

214
00:15:58,166 --> 00:16:00,835
You'd be late for your own funeral
and it nearly was.

215
00:16:00,918 --> 00:16:03,337
-No damage done.
-And who's this?

216
00:16:04,338 --> 00:16:06,674
What are you looking at
with your mouth open?

217
00:16:06,757 --> 00:16:08,718
-Your hair.
-What?

218
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:10,678
I've never seen it like...

219
00:16:12,013 --> 00:16:13,973
I mean...

220
00:16:14,056 --> 00:16:16,767
it's lovely, your hair's lovely.

221
00:16:20,938 --> 00:16:22,940
And that baby you're holding.

222
00:16:24,609 --> 00:16:27,445
That would be your baby.

223
00:16:27,653 --> 00:16:30,490
-Another one of yours, is she?
-She saved my life.

224
00:16:30,573 --> 00:16:33,075
That's a new one.
What was it last time?

225
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:35,745
I didn't even know her.
She was a cloakroom attendant.

226
00:16:35,828 --> 00:16:37,622
I was helping her
look for my ticket.

227
00:16:37,705 --> 00:16:41,334
There were three duffle coats all the same.
Somehow the rack collapsed.

228
00:16:41,417 --> 00:16:43,169
We were under all this stuff.

229
00:16:43,252 --> 00:16:44,420
Were you playing around?

230
00:16:44,504 --> 00:16:46,756
What's it got to do with you
what he gets up to?

231
00:16:46,839 --> 00:16:48,674
-What does he get up to?
-You'd know.

232
00:16:48,758 --> 00:16:52,303
Because I'm that stupid. I play around
and I bring her to meet the missus.

233
00:16:52,386 --> 00:16:54,055
-You silly...
-But you are that stupid.

234
00:16:54,138 --> 00:16:56,599
Can we keep this stuff for back home,
just for now?

235
00:16:56,682 --> 00:16:58,267
What, with the rest of the rubbish?

236
00:16:58,351 --> 00:17:01,854
You bring home cut-price detergents,
tonic water,

237
00:17:01,938 --> 00:17:04,315
Betamax tapes and none of it works.

238
00:17:04,398 --> 00:17:06,859
I'm drowning in your rubbish.

239
00:17:06,943 --> 00:17:10,238
What did he tell you?
Did he say he's this big businessman?

240
00:17:10,321 --> 00:17:14,700
'Cause he's not. He's a failure.
Born failure, that one.

241
00:17:14,784 --> 00:17:16,327
Rose needs a proper father...

242
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:19,205
Jackie, I'm making a living.
It keeps us fed, doesn't it?

243
00:17:19,288 --> 00:17:20,623
Stop it.

244
00:17:22,333 --> 00:17:25,044
You're not like this.
You love each other.

245
00:17:25,127 --> 00:17:27,088
Pete, you never used to
like them mental.

246
00:17:27,171 --> 00:17:29,840
-Or I don't know, maybe you did.
-Jackie, wait, listen...

247
00:17:29,924 --> 00:17:33,427
If you're not careful, there'll be a wedding
and a divorce on the same day.

248
00:17:33,511 --> 00:17:34,595
(BABY CRYING)

249
00:17:34,679 --> 00:17:37,306
Wait here.
Give us a couple of minutes with the missus.

250
00:17:37,390 --> 00:17:40,768
Tell you what, straighten the car up.
Stick it round the corner.

251
00:17:40,851 --> 00:17:42,812
Don't cause any more trouble.

252
00:17:45,565 --> 00:17:47,400
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

253
00:18:04,208 --> 00:18:05,668
Hey, Jack.

254
00:18:35,323 --> 00:18:38,492
I'm not listening.
It's the duffle coats all over again.

255
00:18:38,576 --> 00:18:41,746
Jackie, sometimes a duffle coat
is just a duffle coat.

256
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:44,582
Things will get better soon.
I promise.

257
00:18:44,665 --> 00:18:46,626
I've had enough of
all your daft schemes.

258
00:18:46,709 --> 00:18:48,836
I never know where
the next meal's coming from.

259
00:18:48,919 --> 00:18:52,465
I'll get it right, love. One day soon,
I promise you I'll get it right.

260
00:18:52,548 --> 00:18:53,841
Come on.

261
00:18:57,511 --> 00:19:00,139
Monsters! Going to eat us!

262
00:19:00,222 --> 00:19:03,059
What sort of monsters, sweetheart?
Is it aliens?

263
00:19:08,272 --> 00:19:09,440
Rose!

264
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:15,905
Get in the church!

265
00:19:23,371 --> 00:19:24,872
(SCREECHES)

266
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:28,918
Get in the church!

267
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:37,093
Oh, my God. What are they?

268
00:19:37,176 --> 00:19:38,761
Inside!

269
00:19:40,596 --> 00:19:42,473
-Sarah!
-Stay in there!

270
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:45,685
(REAPER SCREECHING)

271
00:19:49,063 --> 00:19:50,523
(MAN SCREAMING)

272
00:19:59,156 --> 00:20:00,366
In.

273
00:20:09,375 --> 00:20:11,293
(REAPERS SCREECHING)

274
00:20:17,675 --> 00:20:20,469
They can't get in.
Old windows and doors. Okay.

275
00:20:20,678 --> 00:20:23,514
The older something is,
the stronger it is.

276
00:20:23,597 --> 00:20:24,974
What else?

277
00:20:28,185 --> 00:20:30,229
Go and check the other doors.
Move!

278
00:20:30,312 --> 00:20:33,065
What's happening?
What are they? What are they?

279
00:20:33,149 --> 00:20:35,484
There's been an accident in time.
A wound in time.

280
00:20:35,568 --> 00:20:37,445
They're like bacteria,
taking advantage.

281
00:20:37,528 --> 00:20:40,281
What do you mean? Time?
What are you jabbering on about time?

282
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:41,532
I might've known you'd argue.

283
00:20:41,615 --> 00:20:44,493
-Jackie, I'm sick of you complaining.
-How do you know my name?

284
00:20:44,577 --> 00:20:45,828
I've never met you in my life.

285
00:20:45,911 --> 00:20:47,747
You never will
unless I sort this out.

286
00:20:47,830 --> 00:20:50,166
If you don't mind,
I've waited a long time to say this,

287
00:20:50,249 --> 00:20:54,837
Jackie Tyler, do as I say.
Go and check the doors.

288
00:20:55,296 --> 00:20:56,547
Yes, sir.

289
00:20:56,630 --> 00:20:57,882
I should've done that ages ago.

290
00:20:57,965 --> 00:21:00,134
-My dad was out there.
-You can mourn him later.

291
00:21:00,217 --> 00:21:02,678
Now we've got to concentrate
on keeping ourselves alive.

292
00:21:02,762 --> 00:21:05,139
-My dad had...
-There is nothing I can do for him.

293
00:21:05,222 --> 00:21:07,600
No, but he had this phone thing.

294
00:21:07,683 --> 00:21:10,978
I can't get it to work.
I keep getting this voice.

295
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:14,064
Watson, come here. I need you.

296
00:21:14,148 --> 00:21:15,900
That's the very first phone call.

297
00:21:15,983 --> 00:21:17,526
Alexander Graham Bell.

298
00:21:17,610 --> 00:21:19,820
I don't think the telephone's
gonna be much use.

299
00:21:19,904 --> 00:21:21,322
Someone must have
called the police.

300
00:21:21,405 --> 00:21:23,991
The police can't help you now,
no one can.

301
00:21:24,241 --> 00:21:26,827
Nothing in this universe
can harm those things.

302
00:21:26,911 --> 00:21:30,331
Time's been damaged
and they've come to sterilise the wound.

303
00:21:34,919 --> 00:21:37,004
By consuming everything inside.

304
00:21:38,464 --> 00:21:39,965
Is this because...

305
00:21:42,384 --> 00:21:43,803
Is this my fault?

306
00:21:59,026 --> 00:22:00,486
No!

307
00:22:15,918 --> 00:22:19,004
There's smoke coming up from the city.
But no sirens.

308
00:22:19,213 --> 00:22:22,842
I don't think it's just us.
I think these things are all over the place.

309
00:22:22,925 --> 00:22:24,301
Maybe the whole world.

310
00:22:32,560 --> 00:22:34,478
Was that a car?

311
00:22:36,897 --> 00:22:39,483
It's not important.
Don't worry about it.

312
00:23:05,467 --> 00:23:09,555
This mate of yours.
What did he mean, this is your fault?

313
00:23:11,599 --> 00:23:13,767
Don't know. Just everything.

314
00:23:15,019 --> 00:23:16,854
I gave you my car keys.

315
00:23:20,524 --> 00:23:23,402
You don't give your keys
to a complete stranger.

316
00:23:26,322 --> 00:23:28,532
It's like I trusted you.

317
00:23:29,825 --> 00:23:32,620
The moment I met you,
I just did.

318
00:23:35,164 --> 00:23:37,124
A wound in time.

319
00:23:39,835 --> 00:23:41,295
You called me Dad.

320
00:23:42,630 --> 00:23:43,923
I can see it.

321
00:23:45,424 --> 00:23:47,676
In my eyes.

322
00:23:47,760 --> 00:23:49,303
Jackie's attitude.

323
00:23:49,970 --> 00:23:52,181
You sound like her
when you shout.

324
00:24:02,024 --> 00:24:05,569
You are.
You are. You're my Rose.

325
00:24:05,736 --> 00:24:07,529
You're my Rose, grown up.

326
00:24:08,906 --> 00:24:13,619
Dad! My dad. My daddy.

327
00:24:17,748 --> 00:24:18,832
Excuse me.

328
00:24:18,916 --> 00:24:20,751
-Mister...?
-Doctor.

329
00:24:20,834 --> 00:24:23,963
-You seem to know what's going on.
-I give that impression, yeah.

330
00:24:24,046 --> 00:24:26,632
-I just wanted to ask...
-Can you save us?

331
00:24:34,098 --> 00:24:35,557
Who are you two, then?

332
00:24:35,641 --> 00:24:37,726
-Stuart Hoskins.
-Sarah Clark.

333
00:24:38,060 --> 00:24:40,145
And one extra? Boy or girl?

334
00:24:40,980 --> 00:24:43,816
I don't know.
I don't want to know, really.

335
00:24:43,899 --> 00:24:45,859
How did all this get started?

336
00:24:46,777 --> 00:24:49,113
Outside the Beatbox Club,
2:00 in the morning.

337
00:24:49,196 --> 00:24:53,075
Street corner, I'd lost my purse,
didn't have money for a taxi.

338
00:24:54,034 --> 00:24:56,120
- I took her home.
-Then what?

339
00:24:56,912 --> 00:24:58,497
Asked her for a date?

340
00:24:58,789 --> 00:25:02,292
-Wrote his number on my hand.
-Never got rid of her since.

341
00:25:02,376 --> 00:25:04,044
My dad said...

342
00:25:09,216 --> 00:25:13,262
I don't know what this is all about
and I know we're not important...

343
00:25:13,345 --> 00:25:15,389
Who said you're not important?

344
00:25:17,016 --> 00:25:21,353
I've travelled to all sorts of places,
done things you couldn't even imagine.

345
00:25:22,021 --> 00:25:23,230
But you two.

346
00:25:24,732 --> 00:25:29,361
Street corner, 2:00 in the morning,
getting a taxi home.

347
00:25:31,321 --> 00:25:33,449
I've never had a life like that.

348
00:25:34,324 --> 00:25:35,993
Yes.

349
00:25:36,076 --> 00:25:37,745
I'll try and save you.

350
00:25:42,416 --> 00:25:44,460
I'm a dad.

351
00:25:44,543 --> 00:25:46,003
I mean, I'm already a dad

352
00:25:46,086 --> 00:25:49,840
but Rose grows up and she's you.

353
00:25:50,966 --> 00:25:52,259
That's wonderful.

354
00:25:52,342 --> 00:25:55,220
I mean, I suppose I thought
that you'd be a bit useless

355
00:25:55,304 --> 00:25:57,931
what with my useless genes
and all but...

356
00:25:59,224 --> 00:26:01,518
Well, I mean, how did you get here?

357
00:26:01,602 --> 00:26:03,812
-Do you really want to know?
-Yeah.

358
00:26:03,896 --> 00:26:05,564
A time machine.

359
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:09,485
-Time machine?
-Cross my heart.

360
00:26:09,568 --> 00:26:12,196
Do you all have time machines
where you come from?

361
00:26:12,279 --> 00:26:13,906
No, just the Doctor.

362
00:26:14,823 --> 00:26:17,242
Did you know these
things were coming?

363
00:26:17,868 --> 00:26:18,994
No.

364
00:26:19,870 --> 00:26:22,372
God, I don't know,
my head's spinning.

365
00:26:25,167 --> 00:26:26,877
What's the future like?

366
00:26:28,587 --> 00:26:30,339
It's not so different.

367
00:26:30,464 --> 00:26:32,758
What am I like?
Have I gone grey?

368
00:26:37,596 --> 00:26:40,766
Have I gone bald?
Don't tell me I've gone bald.

369
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:50,067
So, if this mate of yours isn't your boyfriend,
and I have to say I'm glad

370
00:26:50,150 --> 00:26:53,695
'cause being your dad and all,
I think he's a bit old for you.

371
00:26:54,029 --> 00:26:56,448
-Have you got a bloke?
-No. I did have.

372
00:26:56,532 --> 00:26:58,158
MUM: Mickey.

373
00:27:02,204 --> 00:27:04,248
Do you know him?

374
00:27:04,331 --> 00:27:08,210
I just didn't recognise him in a suit.
You have to let go of me, sweetheart.

375
00:27:08,293 --> 00:27:09,586
I'm always saying that.

376
00:27:09,670 --> 00:27:12,840
He just grabs hold of what's passing
and holds on for dear life.

377
00:27:12,923 --> 00:27:15,551
God help his poor girlfriend
if he ever gets one.

378
00:27:15,634 --> 00:27:18,595
-Me and Rose were just talking.
-Oh, yeah? Talking?

379
00:27:18,679 --> 00:27:21,014
While the world comes to an end,
what do you do?

380
00:27:21,098 --> 00:27:23,100
Cling to the youngest blonde.

381
00:27:25,060 --> 00:27:26,395
Come on, Mick.

382
00:27:29,898 --> 00:27:31,984
-You can't tell her.
-Why?

383
00:27:32,109 --> 00:27:34,444
I mean,
I really don't want you to tell her.

384
00:27:34,528 --> 00:27:36,947
-You don't want people to know?
-Where I come from,

385
00:27:37,030 --> 00:27:39,908
Jackie doesn't know how
to work the timer on the video recorder.

386
00:27:39,992 --> 00:27:41,869
I showed her that last week.

387
00:27:42,202 --> 00:27:43,328
Point taken.

388
00:27:48,375 --> 00:27:52,796
Rose, you're not going to bring about
the end of the world, are you?

389
00:27:53,672 --> 00:27:54,882
Are you?

390
00:28:00,470 --> 00:28:02,806
Jackie gave her to me to look after.

391
00:28:03,473 --> 00:28:04,975
How times change.

392
00:28:05,726 --> 00:28:07,019
I'd better be careful.

393
00:28:07,102 --> 00:28:10,814
I think I just imprinted myself on Mickey
like a mother chicken.

394
00:28:11,231 --> 00:28:14,776
No. Don't touch the baby.

395
00:28:17,946 --> 00:28:20,199
You're both the same person,
that's a paradox.

396
00:28:20,282 --> 00:28:23,493
We don't want a paradox happening,
not with these things outside.

397
00:28:23,577 --> 00:28:27,372
Anything new, any disturbance in time,
makes them stronger.

398
00:28:27,831 --> 00:28:29,750
A paradox might let them in.

399
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:32,544
I can't do anything right, can I?

400
00:28:32,628 --> 00:28:37,591
Since you asked, no.
So, don't touch the baby.

401
00:28:37,883 --> 00:28:40,886
-I'm not stupid.
-You could have fooled me.

402
00:28:44,806 --> 00:28:46,475
All right...

403
00:28:47,517 --> 00:28:48,769
I'm sorry.

404
00:28:51,772 --> 00:28:53,774
I wasn't really gonna leave you
on your own.

405
00:28:53,857 --> 00:28:54,942
I know.

406
00:28:55,067 --> 00:28:58,779
Between you and me,
I haven't got a plan. No idea.

407
00:29:00,572 --> 00:29:02,491
No way out.

408
00:29:02,616 --> 00:29:04,952
You'll think of something.

409
00:29:05,077 --> 00:29:06,954
The entire Earth's been sterilised.

410
00:29:07,037 --> 00:29:10,916
This, and other places like it,
are all that's left of the human race.

411
00:29:10,999 --> 00:29:14,336
We might hold out for a while,
but nothing can stop those creatures.

412
00:29:14,419 --> 00:29:17,923
They'll get through in the end.
The walls aren't that old.

413
00:29:18,423 --> 00:29:20,550
And there's nothing I can do to stop them.

414
00:29:20,634 --> 00:29:23,720
There used to be laws stopping
this kind of thing from happening.

415
00:29:23,804 --> 00:29:26,014
My people would have stopped this.

416
00:29:27,224 --> 00:29:28,850
But they're all gone.

417
00:29:30,102 --> 00:29:32,354
And now I'm going the same way.

418
00:29:32,437 --> 00:29:34,147
If I'd realised...

419
00:29:37,276 --> 00:29:38,902
Just...

420
00:29:40,570 --> 00:29:42,322
tell me you're sorry.

421
00:29:44,199 --> 00:29:45,409
I am.

422
00:29:46,118 --> 00:29:47,369
I'm sorry.

423
00:30:01,133 --> 00:30:03,468
Have you got something hot?

424
00:30:06,555 --> 00:30:08,098
It's the Tardis key.

425
00:30:16,481 --> 00:30:19,318
It's telling me
it's still connected to the Tardis.

426
00:30:19,401 --> 00:30:22,070
The inside of my ship
was thrown out of the wound

427
00:30:22,154 --> 00:30:23,947
but we can use
this to bring it back.

428
00:30:24,031 --> 00:30:26,867
And once I've got my ship back,
then I can mend everything.

429
00:30:26,950 --> 00:30:30,329
Now, I just need a bit of power.
Has anybody got a battery?

430
00:30:30,954 --> 00:30:32,539
This one big enough?

431
00:30:33,874 --> 00:30:34,958
Fantastic.

432
00:30:35,042 --> 00:30:37,085
Good old Dad. There you go.

433
00:30:38,503 --> 00:30:41,298
Just need to do
a bit of charging up.

434
00:30:41,423 --> 00:30:43,717
And then we can
bring everyone back.

435
00:30:48,138 --> 00:30:50,057
(REAPERS SCREECHING)

436
00:30:51,808 --> 00:30:54,102
(POUNDING ON THE DOORS)

437
00:31:08,950 --> 00:31:12,746
You, erm, you never said why
you came here in the first place.

438
00:31:12,871 --> 00:31:17,501
If I had a time machine, I wouldn't have
thought 1987 was anything special.

439
00:31:17,584 --> 00:31:18,919
Not round here, anyway.

440
00:31:19,002 --> 00:31:22,506
-We just ended up here.
-Lucky for me, eh?

441
00:31:22,589 --> 00:31:25,926
-If you hadn't been there to save me...
-That was just a coincidence.

442
00:31:26,009 --> 00:31:29,888
That was just really good luck.
It's amazing.

443
00:31:33,850 --> 00:31:37,854
So, in the future,
are me and her indoors still together?

444
00:31:39,106 --> 00:31:40,148
Yeah.

445
00:31:41,691 --> 00:31:44,152
-You still living with us?
-Yep.

446
00:31:48,698 --> 00:31:50,575
Am I a good dad?

447
00:31:54,329 --> 00:31:55,789
You...

448
00:31:58,458 --> 00:32:03,171
You told me a bedtime story
every night when I was small.

449
00:32:03,255 --> 00:32:06,299
You were always there,
you never missed one.

450
00:32:11,012 --> 00:32:13,140
And, erm...

451
00:32:14,683 --> 00:32:18,270
you took us for picnics
in the country every Saturday.

452
00:32:20,230 --> 00:32:21,898
You never let us down.

453
00:32:23,608 --> 00:32:25,944
You were there for us all the time.

454
00:32:27,028 --> 00:32:29,489
Someone I could really rely on.

455
00:32:36,621 --> 00:32:38,123
That's not me.

456
00:33:00,145 --> 00:33:03,648
Right, no one touches that key,
have you got that? Don't touch it.

457
00:33:03,732 --> 00:33:07,110
Anyone touches that key,
it'll be, well, zap!

458
00:33:07,319 --> 00:33:11,156
Just leave it be and everything will be fine.
We'll get out. All of us.

459
00:33:11,239 --> 00:33:14,784
Stuart, Sarah, you're gonna get married,
just like I said.

460
00:33:43,021 --> 00:33:46,399
-When time gets sorted out...
-Everybody here forgets what happened.

461
00:33:46,483 --> 00:33:50,654
And don't worry, the thing
that you changed will stay changed.

462
00:33:50,862 --> 00:33:52,864
You mean I'll still be alive.

463
00:33:54,908 --> 00:33:56,910
Though I'm meant to be dead.

464
00:34:01,206 --> 00:34:03,542
That's why I haven't done anything
with my life.

465
00:34:03,625 --> 00:34:05,085
Why it didn't mean anything.

466
00:34:05,168 --> 00:34:07,754
-Doesn't work like that.
-Rubbish.

467
00:34:07,879 --> 00:34:10,590
I was so useless
I couldn't even die properly.

468
00:34:11,675 --> 00:34:13,802
Now it's my fault
all this has happened.

469
00:34:13,885 --> 00:34:16,721
-This is my fault.
-No, love.

470
00:34:16,805 --> 00:34:18,390
I'm your dad.

471
00:34:18,473 --> 00:34:20,767
It's my job for it to be my fault.

472
00:34:20,892 --> 00:34:24,563
Her dad?
How are you her dad?

473
00:34:26,106 --> 00:34:27,816
How old were you? 127

474
00:34:27,899 --> 00:34:31,194
-Oh, that's disgusting.
-Jacks, listen.

475
00:34:32,737 --> 00:34:35,574
-This is Rose.
-Rose?

476
00:34:35,699 --> 00:34:37,242
How sick is that?

477
00:34:37,325 --> 00:34:39,369
Did you give my daughter
a second-hand name?

478
00:34:39,452 --> 00:34:42,205
How many are there?
Do you call them all Rose?

479
00:34:42,289 --> 00:34:44,958
Oh, for God's sake, look.
It's the same Rose.

480
00:34:46,084 --> 00:34:47,419
Rose, no!

481
00:34:51,047 --> 00:34:52,340
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

482
00:34:52,424 --> 00:34:54,301
Everyone, behind me!

483
00:35:08,148 --> 00:35:10,108
I'm the oldest thing in here.

484
00:35:13,361 --> 00:35:14,404
Doctor!

485
00:35:39,638 --> 00:35:41,139
It's cold.

486
00:35:42,807 --> 00:35:44,601
The key's cold.

487
00:35:48,563 --> 00:35:50,440
Oh, my God, he's dead.

488
00:35:55,362 --> 00:35:57,989
This is all my fault.

489
00:35:58,073 --> 00:36:01,368
Both of you, all of you.

490
00:36:02,118 --> 00:36:03,662
The whole world.

491
00:36:13,213 --> 00:36:17,175
This is it. There's nothing we can do.
It's the end.

492
00:37:27,162 --> 00:37:29,414
The Doctor really cared about you.

493
00:37:30,582 --> 00:37:34,711
He didn't want you to go through it again.
Not if there was another way.

494
00:37:35,670 --> 00:37:37,213
Now there isn't.

495
00:37:41,176 --> 00:37:42,802
What are you talking about?

496
00:37:42,886 --> 00:37:45,430
The car that should
have killed me, love.

497
00:37:46,264 --> 00:37:48,308
It's here.

498
00:37:52,270 --> 00:37:54,898
The Doctor worked it out way back but he...

499
00:37:56,149 --> 00:37:57,859
tried to protect me.

500
00:38:01,112 --> 00:38:02,906
Still.

501
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:04,908
He's not in charge anymore.

502
00:38:05,784 --> 00:38:07,535
I am.

503
00:38:08,411 --> 00:38:11,206
-But you can't.
-Who am I, love?

504
00:38:13,583 --> 00:38:14,793
My daddy.

505
00:38:18,463 --> 00:38:20,840
Jackie, look at her.

506
00:38:22,300 --> 00:38:23,760
She's ours.

507
00:38:32,268 --> 00:38:33,436
Of course.

508
00:38:40,193 --> 00:38:42,445
I'm meant to be dead, Jackie.

509
00:38:43,988 --> 00:38:45,865
You're gonna get rid of me at last.

510
00:38:45,949 --> 00:38:47,450
Don't say that.

511
00:38:47,534 --> 00:38:50,662
For once in your life, trust me.
It's got to be done.

512
00:38:50,995 --> 00:38:54,833
You've got to survive
'cause you've got to bring up our daughter.

513
00:39:09,430 --> 00:39:13,601
I never read you those bedtime stories,
I never took you on those picnics.

514
00:39:14,185 --> 00:39:16,145
I was never there for you.

515
00:39:16,771 --> 00:39:18,231
You would've been.

516
00:39:18,565 --> 00:39:20,441
But I can do this for you.

517
00:39:21,526 --> 00:39:23,695
I can be a proper dad to you now.

518
00:39:24,362 --> 00:39:25,697
But it's not fair.

519
00:39:25,780 --> 00:39:27,907
I've had all these extra hours.

520
00:39:28,616 --> 00:39:30,910
No one else in the world
has ever had that.

521
00:39:30,994 --> 00:39:34,289
And on top of that,
I get to see you.

522
00:39:37,792 --> 00:39:39,711
And you're beautiful.

523
00:39:42,630 --> 00:39:44,340
How lucky am I, eh?

524
00:39:45,300 --> 00:39:48,344
So, come on.
Do as your dad says.

525
00:39:57,645 --> 00:39:59,272
You gonna be there for me, love?

526
00:40:03,985 --> 00:40:06,112
Thanks for saving me.

527
00:40:12,285 --> 00:40:13,953
(REAPERS SCREECHING)

528
00:40:39,062 --> 00:40:40,396
Goodbye, love.

529
00:40:58,748 --> 00:41:00,959
Go to him. Quick.

530
00:41:53,928 --> 00:41:56,055
MUM: The driver was just a kid.

531
00:41:57,098 --> 00:42:00,351
He stopped,
he waited for the police.

532
00:42:00,476 --> 00:42:02,186
It wasn't his fault.

533
00:42:03,271 --> 00:42:05,565
For some reason,
Pete just ran out.

534
00:42:08,484 --> 00:42:10,570
People say there was this girl.

535
00:42:11,571 --> 00:42:14,115
And she sat with Pete
while he was dying.

536
00:42:14,198 --> 00:42:15,825
She held his hand.

537
00:42:18,119 --> 00:42:19,704
Then she was gone.

538
00:42:21,539 --> 00:42:23,624
Never found out who she was.

539
00:42:51,527 --> 00:42:54,363
ROSE: Peter Alan Tyler, my dad.

540
00:42:54,447 --> 00:42:56,741
The most wonderful man in the world.

541
00:42:57,575 --> 00:43:01,079
Died 7th November, 1987.

542
00:43:18,346 --> 00:43:19,430
And why are we chasing it?

543
00:43:19,514 --> 00:43:23,643
It's mauve and dangerous, and about
30 seconds from the centre of London.

544
00:43:26,229 --> 00:43:27,313
Rose!

545
00:43:27,396 --> 00:43:29,398
Please let me in, Mummy.

546
00:43:29,482 --> 00:43:31,109
You mustn't let him touch you.

547
00:43:31,192 --> 00:43:33,861
-Are you a doctor?
-I have my moments.

548
00:43:33,945 --> 00:43:35,071
They've all got the same injuries.

549
00:43:35,154 --> 00:43:37,365
Right down to the scar
on the back of the hand.

550
00:43:37,448 --> 00:43:41,244
Physical injuries as plague.

551
00:43:41,994 --> 00:43:43,329
-Hello.
-Hello.

552
00:43:43,454 --> 00:43:45,832
Shall we have
a drink on the balcony?

553
00:43:46,457 --> 00:43:47,834
(ROSE EXCLAIMS)

554
00:43:48,835 --> 00:43:52,130
-I like to think of myself as a criminal.
-I bet you do.

555
00:43:53,923 --> 00:43:55,133
(ROSE SCREAMING)

